  "output": "Confirmed: this is a pure Python/asyncio job-scraper (no React/frontend — `output/` is just generated CV HTML/PDF). I'll adapt the analysis to what's actually here and flag the mismatch up front.\n\n## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\n**Note:** This is a Python/asyncio codebase (fetchers → filters → SQLite store → notifiers), not a React app, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply. I've covered the equivalent categories: DB query patterns, caching, memory, and redundant computation.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nOne `SELECT` per job, in a Python loop, for every fetch run:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n```\n\nWith boards like Microsoft/Amazon/Google returning thousands of listings, that's thousands of round-trips per run (even against local SQLite, this is measurable — and it'll matter more if `jobs.db` ever moves to a networked DB). Fix: batch-fetch existing hashes once, then diff in memory.\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):           # stay under SQLite's var limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update(cur.execute(q, chunk).fetchall() and\n                         {r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in cur.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n\n    cur.executemany(INSERT_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(UPDATE_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n(Fix the double-fetch typo in the sketch above if you implement it — just build `existing` with one `cur.execute(q, chunk).fetchall()` per chunk.) This turns O(N) round-trips into O(N/500) + 3 `executemany` calls.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job — `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` for *every job*, recompiling the same keyword patterns from scratch each time:\n\n```python\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFor N jobs this is N compilations of the same pattern list. Fix: compile once in `filter_jobs` and pass compiled patterns down.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include_re = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_re = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include_re, exclude=exclude_re,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):   # already compiled\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\nCheap win, scales with fetch volume (thousands of jobs × ~2 filter lists compiled from scratch each).\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — wasted deep-copy in `Job.to_row()` — `models.py:71-75`\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # deep-copies every field, including `raw` (the full API payload)\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then immediately throws that copy away\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict()` recursively deep-copies all fields. `raw` holds the full unparsed API response per job (can be a sizable nested dict, especially for Google's `ds:1` blob or Workday postings) — and it gets deep-copied only to be discarded on the next line. This runs once per job per `diff()` call. Fix: build the row dict manually, or exclude `raw` from the copy:\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = {f.name: getattr(self, f.name) for f in fields(self) if f.name != \"raw\"}\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\n\n### 4. Redundant computation — `content_hash` recomputed twice per changed job — `store.py:67-69`\n\n```python\nif row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash:      # sha256 computed here\n    changed.append(job)\n    self._update(cur, job, now)                  # to_row() computes sha256 again\n```\n\n`content_hash` is a `@property` that runs SHA-256 on every access; `_update` recomputes it via `to_row()` right after the comparison already computed it. Minor, but free to fix — compute once and reuse (naturally falls out of the batched rewrite in #1, since you'd hash once per job there).\n\n### 5. Memory pressure (not a leak, but worth flagging) — `Job.raw` held for the whole run\n\nEvery `Job` carries `raw: dict` (the full source payload) for the lifetime of a run. For large boards (Amazon/Microsoft/Google configured with `max_pages=40`, thousands of roles), `fetch_all` accumulates all of them in memory simultaneously before `filter_jobs`/`store.diff` ever run. It's bounded and short-lived (process exits after each run), so not a true leak — but if you ever raise `max_pages` further or add more large boards, this is the thing that'll blow up memory first. If it becomes a problem, drop `raw` right after parsing for sources that don't need it downstream (only `notify_webhook` in `notify.py:53` actually serializes it), or make `raw` optional per-source.\n\n### 6. Caching/concurrency opportunity — sequential pagination — `fetchers.py` (Workday, Twosigma, Optiver, Google, Microsoft, Netflix, Amazon)\n\nEvery paginated fetcher does `for page_n in range(max_pages): await _get_json(...)` — strictly sequential, one page at a time, even though `fetch_all` already runs *different sources* concurrently (`asyncio.Semaphore(concurrency)` at `fetchers.py:773`). For boards with `max_pages=40`, that's up to 40 sequential round-trips per source when only a few sources actually need that many pages.\n\nWorkday explicitly returns `total` in its first response (`fetchers.py:466`), so after page 1 you *know* how many more pages exist and can fire them concurrently:\n\n```python\nasync def fetch_workday(client, source):\n    ...\n    data = await _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={**body, \"offset\": 0})\n    postings = data.get(\"jobPostings\", [])\n    total = data.get(\"total\", len(postings))\n    jobs = [_to_job(p) for p in postings]\n\n    remaining_offsets = range(page_size, min(total, 5000), page_size)\n    pages = await asyncio.gather(*(\n        _get_json(client, cxs, method=\"POST\", json={**body, \"offset\": off})\n        for off in remaining_offsets\n    ))\n    for data in pages:\n        jobs.extend(_to_job(p) for p in data.get(\"jobPostings\", []))\n    return jobs\n```\n\nFor Google/Microsoft/Netflix/Amazon/Two Sigma/Optiver, total isn't known upfront (they stop on first empty/duplicate page), so full concurrency isn't safe — but you could fetch in small concurrent batches (e.g. 4 pages at a time) and stop the batch early if any page comes back empty, cutting wall-clock time roughly 4x on boards that actually use many pages. Worth doing only if run time is currently a pain point — the current sequential approach is simpler and safer against duplicate/rate-limit issues, so I'd only add this if the 12h scheduled run (per `pipeline.md`) is taking long enough to matter.\n\n### 7. Minor — `agent.py:544` Meta token scraping\n\n`fetch_meta` runs 5 separate `re.search` passes over the same HTML page (`lsd`, `rev`, `spin_b`, `spin_t`, plus the initial page fetch). Not hot-path (one page per run), so not worth optimizing — flagging only for completeness since it's the same \"recompute across full text repeatedly\" shape as the filters issue, just at negligible scale.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order:** #1 (N+1 diff) and #2 (regex recompilation) are the two with real, scaling impact given board sizes in the thousands — both are also small, low-risk changes. #3/#4 are cheap wins. #5/#6 only matter if you push `max_pages` up or the scheduled run gets slow.\n",
